    <id>https://doi.org/10.1287/isre.2022.0159</id>
    <title>Does Mobile Technology Integration Enhance Complaint Resolution Efficiency and Equity? An Empirical Study of How an Omnichannel Approach Affects Speed of Resolution of Government Service Requests</title>
    <updated>2026-06-24T00:00:00+00:00</updated>
    <author>
      <name>Catherine Tucker, Yifei Wang, Shuyi Yu</name>
    </author>
    <content>&lt;b&gt;Information Systems Research&lt;/b&gt; &lt;br&gt;This paper examines how integrating mobile touchpoints with existing service channels affects the efficiency and equity of nonemergency complaint resolution for cities. In 2015, Boston integrated its existing citizen app with its phone and website services into a single unified “311” service, where complaints would be handled consistently regardless of submission channel. This was among the first efforts in the United States to bring an omnichannel approach to public services. We document that this change had an unexpected effect. Before integration, the app delivered more equitable service across higher- and lower-income neighborhoods than other channels. After integration, because the app made it easier to submit a broader range of complaints, it was increasingly used in requests on enforcing city codes against other residents. The mobile app allowed quicker resolution of enforcement complaints, especially in richer areas with signs of gentrification. The pattern appears to be driven by the economics of density: residents in wealthier neighborhoods are more likely to submit multiple enforcement requests simultaneously. Complaints requiring citations were processed more quickly when related requests came from geographically concentrated areas rather than dispersed locations.</content>
    <link href="https://doi.org/10.1287/isre.2022.0159"/>
    <category term="Information Systems Research"/>
    <published>2026-06-24T00:00:00+00:00</published>
